hints_latex:
Multiply \emph{B} with a general matrix

\begin{align*}
C = \begin{bmatrix}
a & d \\ b & e \\ c & f
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

and then solve the resulting four equations.

sols_latex:
Let $C = \begin{bmatrix} a & d \\ b & e \\ c & f \end{bmatrix}$. Then
multiplying out the required matrix gives

\begin{align*}
\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix}
= BC &= 
\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & -1 \\ -3 & 1 & 0 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} a & d \\ b & e \\ c & f \end{bmatrix}\\
&= \begin{bmatrix} (1)(a)+(0)(b) + (-1)(c) & (1)(d) + (0)(e) + (-1)(f) \\ (-3)(a) + (1)(b) + (0)(c) & (-3)(d) + (1)(e) + (0)(f) \end{bmatrix}\\
&= \begin{bmatrix} a-c & d-f \\ -3a + b & -3d + e \end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

This gives the equations

\begin{align*}
a-c &= 1\\
d-f &= 0 \\
-3a + b &= 0 \\
-3d + e &= 1
\end{align*}

Setting simple values like $a=1$ and $e=1$ gives us that
$b=3,c=0,d=0,f=0$. This is a valid solution and thus such a matrix C
exists and is given by

$C = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 3 & 1 \\ 0 & 0 \end{bmatrix}$

sols_raw:
Let &lt;math>C = \begin{bmatrix} a &amp; d \\ b &amp; e \\ c &amp; f \end{bmatrix} &lt;/math>. Then multiplying out the required matrix gives

&lt;math>
\begin{align}
\begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix}
= BC &amp;= 
\begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 &amp; -1 \\ -3 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} a &amp; d \\ b &amp; e \\ c &amp; f \end{bmatrix}\\
&amp;= \begin{bmatrix} (1)(a)+(0)(b) + (-1)(c) &amp; (1)(d) + (0)(e) + (-1)(f) \\ (-3)(a) + (1)(b) + (0)(c) &amp; (-3)(d) + (1)(e) + (0)(f) \end{bmatrix}\\
&amp;= \begin{bmatrix} a-c &amp; d-f \\ -3a + b &amp; -3d + e \end{bmatrix}
\end{align}
&lt;/math>

This gives the equations

&lt;math>
\begin{align}
a-c &amp;= 1\\
d-f &amp;= 0 \\
-3a + b &amp;= 0 \\
-3d + e &amp;= 1
\end{align}
&lt;/math>

Setting simple values like &lt;math>a=1 &lt;/math> and &lt;math> e=1 &lt;/math> gives us that &lt;math>b=3,c=0,d=0,f=0&lt;/math>. This is a valid solution and thus such a matrix C exists and is given by 

&lt;math>C = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 \\ 3 &amp; 1 \\ 0 &amp; 0 \end{bmatrix} &lt;/math>
Proceeding as in hint 3, we find the inverse of

&lt;math>
 \begin{bmatrix}
1 &amp; 0 \\ -3 &amp; 1
\end{bmatrix}
&lt;/math>

which is given by 

&lt;math>
 \begin{bmatrix}
1 &amp; 0 \\ 3 &amp; 1
\end{bmatrix}
&lt;/math>

Thus, a matrix C that will work is

&lt;math>
 \begin{bmatrix}
1 &amp; 0 \\ 3 &amp; 1 \\ 0 &amp; 0 
\end{bmatrix}
&lt;/math>

Since the zeroes at the bottom will cancel any terms in the last column of B once you perform the matrix multiplication &lt;math>BC &lt;/math>.

